2. Mathematical Preliminaries

We assume familiarity with basic probability theory, measure theory, and Markov decision processes. The following notations and concepts will be used throughout.

· Spaces: Let \mathcal{I} and \Theta be finite sets representing user intents and cognitive parameters (e.g., expertise level, reasoning style, cognitive load). The product space \mathcal{X} = \mathcal{I} \times \Theta is therefore finite. Finiteness ensures compactness of the belief simplex and simplifies convergence arguments; extensions to infinite spaces are possible with additional continuity conditions, which we note where relevant. A concrete example is \Theta = \{\text{novice}, \text{intermediate}, \text{expert}\}.
· Probability measures: \Delta(\mathcal{X}) is the set of all probability distributions over \mathcal{X}. For b \in \Delta(\mathcal{X}), \operatorname{supp}(b) denotes its support.
· Entropy: For a distribution b, H(b) = -\sum_{x} b(x) \log b(x) (with natural logarithm throughout, giving entropy in nats).
· Martingales: A sequence of random variables \{X_n\} is a martingale if \mathbb{E}[X_{n+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_n] = X_n. The martingale convergence theorem provides almost‑sure limits for bounded martingales.
· Markov decision processes (MDPs): A belief MDP is a fully observable MDP whose state is a belief distribution over unobserved variables. The Bellman operator is defined as (TV)(b) = \max_a [r(b,a) + \gamma \int V(b') \, \mathbb{P}(db' \mid b,a)].

