3. Formal Model of Adaptive Questioning Intelligence

We now define the core components of AQI.

Definition 1 (Augmented Belief State)

Let \mathcal{I} be the space of possible user intents and \Theta the space of user cognitive parameters. The epistemic state at turn t is the joint posterior distribution over intent and cognitive type given the dialogue history h_t:

b_t(i,\theta) = \mathbb{P}(I = i, \Theta = \theta \mid h_t), \qquad (i,\theta) \in \mathcal{I} \times \Theta.

The marginal intent belief is b_t(i) = \sum_{\theta} b_t(i,\theta).

The dialogue history h_t includes all previous questions, answers, and the system’s own utterances. The belief is updated recursively using the user’s response.

Proposition 1 (Hierarchical Bayesian Update)

Assume the user’s response r to a question q depends only on the true intent I and their cognitive parameters \Theta through a known conditional probability P(r \mid q, i, \theta). Then, after asking q and receiving answer r, the belief updates as

b_{t+1}(i,\theta) = \frac{b_t(i,\theta) \; P(r \mid q, i, \theta)}{\sum_{i',\theta'} b_t(i',\theta') \; P(r \mid q, i', \theta')}.

Proof. This is a direct application of Bayes’ theorem, using the fact that P(r \mid q, h_t, i, \theta) = P(r \mid q, i, \theta) because the response is conditionally independent of the history given the true state. ∎

The update is deterministic given the observed response; hence the belief evolves as a function of the chosen question and the stochastic answer.

---

Definition 2 (Expected Value of Perfect Information)

Let V^*(b) be the optimal expected downstream task success probability (or any bounded reward) when the agent decides to answer immediately from belief state b (the “terminal value” function). The expected value of perfect information (EVPI) for a clarification question q in belief b_t is

\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t) = \mathbb{E}_{r \sim P(\cdot \mid q, b_t)}\bigl[ V^*(b_{t+1}(r)) \bigr] - V^*(b_t),

where

P(r \mid q, b_t) = \sum_{i,\theta} b_t(i,\theta) \, P(r \mid q, i, \theta)

is the predictive distribution of the answer.

EVPI measures the expected improvement in terminal value if the agent asks q and then optimally answers after seeing the response, compared to answering immediately.

---

Lemma 1 (Adaptive Identifiability)

Let x^* be the true state and fix a false state x \neq x^*. Suppose the policy selects, infinitely often, questions q for which the Kullback–Leibler divergence

D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \,\|\, P(\cdot \mid q, x^*)\bigr) \geq \delta > 0

for some constant \delta. Then, under the true distribution x^*,

\sum_{t=1}^\infty \log \frac{P(r_t \mid q_t, x)}{P(r_t \mid q_t, x^*)} = -\infty \quad \text{almost surely},

and consequently the normalised likelihood ratio process L_t(x) = \frac{b_0(x)}{b_0(x^*)}\prod_{s=1}^t \frac{P(r_s \mid q_s, x)}{P(r_s \mid q_s, x^*)} converges to zero almost surely.

Proof. For each step t, let Z_t = \log \frac{P(r_t \mid q_t, x)}{P(r_t \mid q_t, x^*)}. Conditioned on the history up to time t-1 (which includes q_t), the random variable Z_t has conditional expectation

\mathbb{E}[Z_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] = - D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q_t, x) \,\|\, P(\cdot \mid q_t, x^*)\bigr) \leq -\delta

whenever q_t is one of the informative questions. For steps where the question is not informative, the conditional expectation is non‑positive (since KL divergence is non‑negative). Thus the partial sums S_t = \sum_{s=1}^t Z_s form a supermartingale with negative drift on the informative steps.

Define the non‑negative process U_t = S_t + \delta \sum_{s=1}^t \mathbf{1}_{\{q_s \text{ informative}\}}. Because S_t is a supermartingale, the sequence \{U_t\} is a supermartingale as well. By the Robbins–Siegmund theorem (see e.g., [7, Lemma 5.1]), if \sum_t \mathbb{E}[\max(0, Z_t) \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] < \infty (which holds because the increments are bounded), then U_t converges almost surely to a finite limit. Since the number of informative steps is infinite, the sum \delta \sum_{s=1}^t \mathbf{1}_{\{q_s \text{ informative}\}} diverges to +\infty, forcing S_t \to -\infty almost surely. Hence L_t(x) \propto \exp(S_t) \to 0 a.s. ∎

---

Theorem 1 (Ouadi’s Convergence Theorem — Almost‑Sure Convergence of Belief)

Let \mathcal{X} = \mathcal{I} \times \Theta be a finite set. Assume the true state is x^* = (i^*, \theta^*). For each question q, define the likelihood function L_q(x) = P(\cdot \mid q, x). The family \{L_q\}_{q \in \mathcal{Q}} is said to be strictly identifiable if for every x \neq x^*, there exists a sequence of questions q_1, q_2, \dots (possibly dependent on previous responses) such that

\prod_{t=1}^{\infty} \frac{L_{q_t}(x)(r_t)}{L_{q_t}(x^*)(r_t)} = 0 \quad \text{almost surely under } x^*,

where r_t are the observed answers. Moreover, assume there exists a uniform lower bound \delta > 0 such that P(r \mid q, x^*) \geq \delta for all q that are asked infinitely often. Then, under any policy that eventually asks infinitely many questions that together satisfy strict identifiability, the joint belief b_t converges almost surely to the Dirac measure \delta_{x^*}.

Remark. This result will be referred to as Ouadi’s Convergence Theorem in the sequel, acknowledging the conceptual origin of the adaptive questioning intelligence framework.

Proof. The sequence \{b_t\} is a bounded martingale with respect to the filtration generated by the dialogue history. Indeed, by Proposition 1,

\mathbb{E}[b_{t+1}(x) \mid h_t] = \sum_r \frac{b_t(x) P(r \mid q_t, x)}{\sum_{x'} b_t(x') P(r \mid q_t, x')} \cdot P(r \mid q_t, b_t) = b_t(x),

so each component is a martingale bounded in [0,1]. By the martingale convergence theorem, each converges almost surely to a random limit b_\infty(x).

Now consider a sample path where convergence occurs. Suppose, for contradiction, that there exists x \neq x^* such that b_\infty(x) > 0. For each false state x \neq x^*, define the normalised likelihood ratio process

L_t(x) = \frac{b_0(x)}{b_0(x^*)} \prod_{s=1}^{t} \frac{P(r_s \mid q_s, x)}{P(r_s \mid q_s, x^*)}.

Under the true state x^*, the process \{L_t(x)\} is a non‑negative martingale (because each factor has conditional expectation 1). By Lemma 1, if the policy selects infinitely many questions that separate x from x^* (i.e., with D_{\mathrm{KL}} > 0), then L_t(x) \to 0 a.s. Strict identifiability guarantees that such informative questions are asked infinitely often, because otherwise the product would not converge to zero. Hence L_t(x) \to 0 a.s. for all false x. Moreover, the posterior ratio satisfies

\frac{b_t(x)}{b_t(x^*)} = L_t(x) \cdot \frac{\sum_{x'} b_t(x')}{\sum_{x'} b_t(x')} = L_t(x)

(since the sum of all posterior masses is 1). Therefore b_t(x)/b_t(x^*) \to 0 a.s., and consequently b_t(x) \to 0 a.s. for all x \neq x^*. By the martingale convergence of b_t(x^*), it follows that b_t(x^*) \to 1 a.s. Thus b_\infty(x) = 0 for all x \neq x^* and b_\infty(x^*) = 1 almost surely. ∎

