Theorem 2 (Myopic Optimality of EVPI under One‑Step Horizon)

For a given belief b_t and a per‑question cost \lambda C(q,t) (including cognitive load and latency), the question

q^* = \arg\max_{q} \Bigl( \mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t) - \lambda \, C(q,t) \Bigr)

maximises the expected one‑step improvement in terminal value. Moreover, if the terminal value function V^* is \alpha-Lipschitz in total variation distance on \Delta(\mathcal{X}), i.e.,

|V^*(b) - V^*(b')| \leq \alpha \, \|b - b'\|_{\mathrm{TV}},

then

|\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t)| \leq \alpha \, \|P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) - P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\|_{\mathrm{TV}}.

Proof. The myopic optimality follows directly from the definition of EVPI: the expected net gain of asking q and then acting optimally is \mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t) - \lambda C(q,t). Hence the greedy selection maximises this gain.

For the bound, observe that

\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t) = \mathbb{E}_{r}[V^*(b_{t+1}(r))] - V^*(b_t) = \mathbb{E}_{r}[V^*(b_{t+1}(r)) - V^*(b_t)].

By the Lipschitz property,

|V^*(b_{t+1}(r)) - V^*(b_t)| \leq \alpha \|b_{t+1}(r) - b_t\|_{\mathrm{TV}}.

Now note that the total variation distance between the posterior and prior is at most the total variation distance between the predictive distributions (a consequence of the fact that the Bayesian update is a contraction in TV; see, e.g., Lemma 2.1 in [5]). Thus

\|b_{t+1}(r) - b_t\|_{\mathrm{TV}} \leq \|P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) - P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\|_{\mathrm{TV}}.

Taking expectation over r and using the triangle inequality gives the desired bound. ∎

---

Corollary 1 (Information‑Theoretic Bound)

Under the assumptions of Theorem 2, we have

|\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t)| \leq \alpha \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \mathbb{E}_{x \sim b_t}\Bigl[ D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \,\|\, P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\bigr) \Bigr]},

which is further bounded by \alpha \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b_t)} if we use the inequality

\mathbb{E}_{x \sim b_t}\bigl[ D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})) \bigr] \leq I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b_t) + D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) \| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})).

For practical purposes, many Bayesian experimental design works simply bound EVPI by \alpha \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b_t)}, which is a convenient proxy (see e.g., [14]).

Proof. From Theorem 2,

|\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t)| \leq \alpha \, \|P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) - P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\|_{\mathrm{TV}}.

By Pinsker’s inequality,

\|P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) - P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\|_{\mathrm{TV}} \leq \sqrt{\frac12 D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) \big\| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\bigr)}.

Using the convexity of KL in its first argument (Jensen’s inequality),

D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) \big\| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\bigr) \leq \mathbb{E}_{x \sim b_t}\bigl[ D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \big\| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})\bigr) \bigr].

The right‑hand side is the expected KL divergence between the predictive under a single state and the predictive under the true state. This quantity is closely related to mutual information; in particular,

\mathbb{E}_{x \sim b_t}\bigl[ D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})) \bigr] = I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b_t) + D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P(\cdot \mid q, b_t) \| P(\cdot \mid q, \delta_{x^*})).

Thus the simpler bound |\mathrm{EVPI}| \leq \alpha \sqrt{\frac12 I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b_t)} is a slightly looser but practically convenient bound, often used in the experimental design literature. ∎

Remark. The corollary shows that maximising mutual information is a valid proxy for EVPI up to a constant factor, which justifies the common heuristic of selecting questions that maximise expected information gain.

