Definition 4 (Epistemic Stabilisation Error)

Define the epistemic error at time t as the entropy of the belief:

e_t = H(b_t) = -\sum_{i,\theta} b_t(i,\theta) \log b_t(i,\theta).

This measures the remaining uncertainty about the joint state (I,\Theta).

---

Theorem 4 (Entropy Contraction under Informative Questions)

Assume that there exists a function \beta: (0, \infty) \to (0, \infty) such that for any belief b with H(b) > \varepsilon, the policy selects a question q satisfying

I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b) \geq \beta(\varepsilon) > 0.

Then the entropy process e_t converges to zero almost surely.

Proof. The mutual information identity gives

\mathbb{E}[e_{t+1} \mid b_t] = e_t - I(I,\Theta; r \mid q_t, b_t).

Consider any \varepsilon > 0. On the event that e_t > \varepsilon, we have \mathbb{E}[e_{t+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_t] \le e_t - \beta(\varepsilon). Thus the process e_t is a supermartingale with a uniform negative drift whenever it stays above \varepsilon. Because e_t is bounded between 0 and \log |\mathcal{X}|, it must eventually fall below \varepsilon almost surely; otherwise the drift would force the expectation to become negative, which is impossible. Hence for every \varepsilon > 0, the stopping time \tau_\varepsilon = \inf\{t \ge 0 : e_t \le \varepsilon\} is almost surely finite.

Now suppose, for contradiction, that there exists a sample path where e_t does not converge to zero. Then there exists some \eta > 0 such that e_t > \eta infinitely often. However, because \tau_{\eta/2} is finite a.s., after that time e_t never exceeds \eta/2, which contradicts the existence of infinitely many visits above \eta. Therefore e_t \to 0 almost surely. ∎

Sufficient condition for existence of \beta(\varepsilon). If the question set \mathcal{Q} is such that for any two distinct states x, x' \in \mathcal{X}, there exists a question q with P(\cdot \mid q, x) \neq P(\cdot \mid q, x'), then the mutual information I(I,\Theta; r \mid q, b) is positive for any b that is not a point mass. Moreover, because \mathcal{X} is finite and the mutual information is continuous in b on the compact set \{b : H(b) \ge \varepsilon\} (the set is closed since entropy is continuous, and closed subsets of the compact simplex are compact), the minimum over such beliefs is attained and positive, yielding \beta(\varepsilon) > 0. Thus the assumption holds for any policy that always selects such a separating question whenever H(b) > \varepsilon.

