5. Illustrative Example

To make the theory concrete, consider a simplified scenario with two intents \mathcal{I} = \{A, B\} and two cognitive types \Theta = \{\text{novice}, \text{expert}\}. The user’s response to a question q is modelled as a binary correct/incorrect signal. The conditional probabilities are:

State (I,\Theta) P(\text{correct} \mid q)
(A, \text{novice}) 0.6
(B, \text{novice}) 0.4
(A, \text{expert}) 0.9
(B, \text{expert}) 0.1

Suppose the current belief is uniform over the four joint states, i.e., b_t(i,\theta) = 0.25 for all (i,\theta). We compute the mutual information I(I,\Theta; r \mid q) in nats (natural logarithms).

The predictive distribution of the answer is

P(\text{correct}) = \frac14(0.6+0.4+0.9+0.1) = \frac14(2.0) = 0.5, \quad P(\text{incorrect}) = 0.5.

The marginal entropy of r is H(0.5) = -0.5 \ln 0.5 - 0.5 \ln 0.5 = \ln 2 \approx 0.6931 nats.

The conditional entropy of the answer given the state is

H(r \mid I,\Theta) = \sum_{i,\theta} \frac14 H(r \mid i,\theta) = \frac14 \bigl( H(0.6) + H(0.4) + H(0.9) + H(0.1) \bigr),

where H(p) = -p \ln p - (1-p) \ln (1-p). Numerically,

H(0.6)= -0.6\ln0.6 - 0.4\ln0.4 \approx 0.6730,\quad H(0.4)=0.6730,\quad H(0.9)=0.3251,\quad H(0.1)=0.3251.

Thus \mathbb{E}[H(r \mid I,\Theta)] \approx \frac14(0.6730+0.6730+0.3251+0.3251) = 0.4990 nats.

Hence the mutual information is

I(I,\Theta; r \mid q) = H(r) - H(r \mid I,\Theta) \approx 0.6931 - 0.4990 = 0.1941 \text{ nats}.

Assuming the Lipschitz constant \alpha of V^* is known, Corollary 1 gives the bound

|\mathrm{EVPI}(q \mid b_t)| \leq \alpha \sqrt{\frac12 \times 0.1941} \approx 0.3115\,\alpha.

This provides a quantitative justification for asking the question when the potential information gain outweighs the cost.

---

6. Conclusion

We have presented Adaptive Questioning Intelligence, a mathematically rigorous framework for conversational agents that actively seek information through clarification questions while adapting to the user’s cognitive state. The core innovations are: (i) a joint belief over intent and cognitive parameters, (ii) a value‑of‑information criterion (EVPI) for question selection, (iii) a belief MDP formulation with existence and uniqueness guarantees, (iv) convergence proofs for belief and entropy under identifiability and uniform informativeness, and (v) an extension to rate‑limited interactions via a trajectory‑level rate‑distortion objective. This work provides a mathematically coherent foundation for epistemic dialogue control, opening the door to principled, personalised, and efficient conversational AI systems.

Future work will focus on learning the user response model from interaction, scaling the belief MDP to large state spaces using function approximation, and conducting extensive empirical evaluations to validate the theoretical predictions.

