Appendix B: Proof of Lemma 1 (Adaptive Identifiability) – Full Details

We provide a rigorous proof of Lemma 1 using the Robbins–Siegmund theorem [7, Lemma 5.1] (also known as the “almost supermartingale” convergence theorem).

Lemma 1 (restated). Let x^* be the true state and fix a false state x \neq x^*. Suppose the policy selects, infinitely often, questions q for which D_{\mathrm{KL}}(P(\cdot \mid q, x) \| P(\cdot \mid q, x^*)) \ge \delta > 0. Then

\sum_{t=1}^\infty \log \frac{P(r_t \mid q_t, x)}{P(r_t \mid q_t, x^*)} = -\infty \quad \text{a.s.},

and consequently L_t(x) \to 0 a.s.

Proof. Define Z_t = \log \frac{P(r_t \mid q_t, x)}{P(r_t \mid q_t, x^*)}. For each t, conditioned on \mathcal{F}_{t-1} (which includes q_t and all previous observations), we have

\mathbb{E}[Z_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] = -D_{\mathrm{KL}}\bigl(P(\cdot \mid q_t, x) \| P(\cdot \mid q_t, x^*)\bigr) \le -\delta \mathbf{1}_{\{q_t \text{ informative}\}}.

Let S_t = \sum_{s=1}^t Z_s. Define A_t = S_t + \delta \sum_{s=1}^t \mathbf{1}_{\{q_s \text{ informative}\}}. Because the drift of S_t is at most -\delta on informative steps, the process A_t is a supermartingale: indeed,

\mathbb{E}[A_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] \le A_{t-1} + \mathbb{E}[Z_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] + \delta \mathbf{1}_{\{q_t \text{ informative}\}} \le A_{t-1}.

Moreover, A_t is non‑negative because S_t might be negative but the added term compensates. The Robbins–Siegmund theorem states that for a non‑negative supermartingale \{A_t\} with \sum_t \mathbb{E}[\max(0, \Delta A_t) \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] < \infty, the sequence converges a.s. to a finite limit. Here \Delta A_t = Z_t + \delta \mathbf{1}_{\{q_t \text{ informative}\}}. Since |Z_t| is bounded (the response space is finite and likelihoods are positive), the conditional expectations are bounded, so the sum condition holds. Therefore A_t converges a.s. to a finite limit.

Now, because the policy selects infinitely many informative steps, \delta \sum_{s=1}^t \mathbf{1}_{\{q_s \text{ informative}\}} \to +\infty. Since A_t converges, it follows that S_t = A_t - \delta \sum_{s=1}^t \mathbf{1}_{\{q_s \text{ informative}\}} \to -\infty a.s. Hence \exp(S_t) \to 0 a.s. Finally,

L_t(x) = \frac{b_0(x)}{b_0(x^*)} \prod_{s=1}^t \frac{P(r_s \mid q_s, x)}{P(r_s \mid q_s, x^*)} = \frac{b_0(x)}{b_0(x^*)} \exp(S_t) \to 0 \quad \text{a.s.}

∎

