Appendix C: Strict Identifiability and Posterior Consistency

The strict identifiability condition in Theorem 1 can be related to standard conditions for Bayesian consistency with non‑i.i.d. observations. For finite state spaces, the condition that for each false x there exists a sequence of questions (possibly dependent on previous responses) such that the infinite product of likelihood ratios vanishes a.s. is equivalent to requiring that the policy eventually asks infinitely many questions that separate x from x^* with a positive KL divergence. This is essentially the “identifiability” assumption used in the theory of sequential Bayesian learning (see, e.g., [Doob 1949, Schwartz 1965]). In our adaptive setting, Lemma 1 provides the bridge: if the policy asks infinitely many separating questions, the product vanishes.

We note that the uniform lower bound P(r \mid q, x^*) \ge \delta ensures that no response is impossible, which avoids division by zero in the Bayesian update and guarantees that the likelihood ratio process is well‑defined.

