Appendix D: Detailed Contraction Proof for the Belief MDP (Theorem 3)

We expand the proof of the contraction property for the Bellman operator T defined on the space of bounded continuous functions V: \mathcal{B} \to \mathbb{R} with the supremum norm \|V\|_\infty = \sup_{b \in \mathcal{B}} |V(b)|.

The transition kernel for asking a question q is given by

\mathbb{P}(b' \mid b,q) = \sum_{r} \mathbf{1}_{b' = f(b,q,r)} \, P(r \mid q,b),

where f(b,q,r) is the deterministic update. The kernel is a continuous mapping from b to the space of probability measures over \mathcal{B} (with the weak topology), because both P(r \mid q,b) and f(b,q,r) are continuous.

Define the operator T by

(TV)(b) = \max_{a \in \mathcal{A}} \left\{ r(b,a) + \gamma \int_{\mathcal{B}} V(b') \, \mathbb{P}(db' \mid b,a) \right\}.

For two bounded continuous functions V_1, V_2 and any b, we have

|(TV_1)(b) - (TV_2)(b)| \le \gamma \max_{a} \left| \int_{\mathcal{B}} (V_1(b') - V_2(b')) \, \mathbb{P}(db' \mid b,a) \right| \le \gamma \|V_1 - V_2\|_\infty.

The first inequality uses the fact that the maximum of a set of numbers is Lipschitz in each argument with constant 1; the second uses that the integral of a function bounded by \|V_1-V_2\|_\infty with respect to a probability measure is bounded by the same constant. Taking supremum over b yields \|T V_1 - T V_2\|_\infty \le \gamma \|V_1 - V_2\|_\infty, so T is a \gamma-contraction. Since \mathcal{B} is compact and the mapping is continuous, the space of bounded continuous functions is complete, and Banach’s fixed point theorem gives a unique V^*. Optimality follows from standard policy iteration arguments for discounted MDPs.

