Appendix E: Mutual Information Identity and Entropy Contraction

The identity used in Theorem 4 is fundamental:

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1}) \mid b_t] = H(b_t) - I(I,\Theta; r \mid q_t, b_t).

Here H(b_t) is the entropy of the joint distribution over \mathcal{X}. The derivation is standard:

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1}) \mid b_t] = \mathbb{E}_{r \sim P(\cdot \mid q_t, b_t)} \left[ -\sum_{x} b_{t+1}(x) \log b_{t+1}(x) \right].

Using the update rule, one can show that

\mathbb{E}[H(b_{t+1}) \mid b_t] = H(b_t) - \sum_{x} b_t(x) \sum_{r} P(r \mid q_t, x) \log \frac{P(r \mid q_t, x)}{P(r \mid q_t, b_t)}.

The double sum is exactly the mutual information I(I,\Theta; r \mid q_t, b_t). This identity holds for any belief b_t and question q_t.

