Appendix F: Lagrangian Duality for the Rate‑Distortion Constraint

We provide additional justification for the duality in Theorem 5. Consider the constrained problem

\max_{\pi} \mathbb{E}_\pi\left[\sum_{t=0}^\infty \gamma^t r_t\right] \quad \text{s.t.} \quad \limsup_{T\to\infty} \frac{1}{T} \mathbb{E}_\pi\left[\sum_{t=1}^T I(\Theta; a_t \mid h_t)\right] \le R.

Define the Lagrangian \mathcal{L}(\pi, \beta) = \mathbb{E}_\pi[\sum_t \gamma^t r_t] - \beta \left( \limsup_T \frac{1}{T} \mathbb{E}_\pi[\sum_{t=1}^T I(\Theta; a_t \mid h_t)] - R \right). For a fixed \beta \ge 0, the unconstrained problem \max_\pi \mathbb{E}_\pi[\sum_t \gamma^t r_t - \beta I(\Theta; a_t \mid h_t)] is a standard MDP with a bounded penalty, and its optimal value is concave in \beta. Under Slater’s condition (existence of a policy with strict inequality), strong duality holds, i.e.,

\max_{\pi \text{ feasible}} \mathbb{E}_\pi\left[\sum_t \gamma^t r_t\right] = \min_{\beta \ge 0} \max_{\pi} \mathcal{L}(\pi, \beta).

The optimal \beta can be found by convex optimization. The Bellman equation given in Definition 5 arises from the inner maximization for fixed \beta. For details, see [9, Chapter 4] and [8].

