Appendix G: Remarks on Computational Complexity and Approximation

The belief MDP formulation leads to an exponentially large state space (in |\mathcal{X}|). Exact dynamic programming is infeasible for any realistic problem. Below we summarise the main approximation approaches referenced in Section 4.2.

G.1 Point‑Based Value Iteration (PBVI) [10]

PBVI maintains a finite set of reachable belief points \mathcal{B}_\text{rep}. The value function is approximated as a piecewise‑linear and convex function, represented by a set of vectors. The algorithm alternates between value update (using only the representative points) and expansion of the belief set.

G.2 SARSOP [11]

SARSOP (Successive Approximations of the Reachable Space under Optimal Policies) uses a tree search to focus on beliefs that are reachable under optimal policies. It prunes large parts of the belief space using upper and lower bounds, achieving efficiency in many POMDP domains.

G.3 Deep Reinforcement Learning

For large or continuous state spaces, one can parameterise the policy \pi_\theta(b) with a neural network and use policy gradient methods to optimise the expected cumulative reward, where the EVPI can be estimated via Monte Carlo simulation. This approach scales to high‑dimensional problems but loses the theoretical guarantees of exact solution.


